icanized form of German   Lennert   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Leonard","meanings":["English; French (<b>Léonard</b>); Walloon (mainly <b>Léonard</b>): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>leo</i> ‘lion’ (a late addition to the vocabulary of ancient Germanic name elements, taken from Latin) + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’, which was taken to England by the Normans. A Christian saint of this name, who is supposed to have lived in the 6th century, but about whom nothing is known except for a largely fictional life dating from half a millennium later, was popular throughout Europe in the early Middle Ages and was regarded as the patron of peasants and horses. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Leonardo  , Polish, Slovenian, etc.   Lenart   or   Lenard  , and probably also their derivatives. Compare   Larned  ,   Learned  , and   Yenor  .","Irish (Fermanagh): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Fhionáin</b> or of   Langan  .","German: variant of   Leonhard  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Lennard II was born in 1399, in Clavering, Essex, England, his father, John Lennard I, was 29 and his mother, Margaret Woolam, was 29. He married Sarah Ann of Clavering in 1421, in Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1429, in Essex, England, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1399–1429":"1399–1429","1399–1459":"1399–1459","1399–Female":"1399–Surnud","1429–1462":"1429–1462","1370–1407":"1370–1407","1370–1398":"1370–1398","1459":"1459","1399":"1399","1